---
    âœ… Conditionals (Hypothetical Sentences) - Explanation

    ğŸ”¹ Zero Conditional
    Describes general facts or scientific truths.
    Structure: If + present simple, present simple
    âœ… Example: If you heat water, it boils.
    ğŸ“Œ Key Point: Used to express universal truths or natural laws.

    ğŸ”¹ First Conditional
    Describes a possible future event that could happen.
    Structure: If + present simple, will + verb
    âœ… Example: If it rains, I will stay home.
    ğŸ“Œ Key Point: Used when talking about real and likely future situations.

    ğŸ”¹ Second Conditional
    Describes an unreal or hypothetical situation in the present or future.
    Structure: If + past simple, would + verb
    âœ… Example: If I had more time, I would travel.
    ğŸ“Œ Key Point: Used for unlikely or impossible situations that differ from reality.

    ğŸ”¹ Third Conditional
    Describes an unreal or hypothetical past event that did not happen.
    Structure: If + past perfect, would have + past participle
    âœ… Example: If I had studied, I would have passed.
    ğŸ“Œ Key Point: Used to talk about regrets or missed opportunities in the past.

    ğŸ”¹ Mixed Conditional
    Describes how a past event affects the present.
    Structure: If + past perfect, would + verb (present)
    âœ… Example: If I had saved money, I would be rich now.
    ğŸ“Œ Key Point: Expresses the relationship between a past action and its present consequence.

    ğŸ“ Summary:
    Zero Conditional â†’ General facts / Scientific truths
    First Conditional â†’ Possible future events
    Second Conditional â†’ Unreal situations (Present/Future)
    Third Conditional â†’ Unreal past situations (Did not happen)
    Mixed Conditional â†’ Past events affecting the present
    ğŸ“Œ In TOEIC, First and Second Conditionals appear frequently, so focus on those! ğŸš€



